\mt1 1CHRONICLES
\c 1
\p
\v 1 Adam, Seth, Enosh;
\v 2 Kenan, Mahalalel, Jared;
\v 3 Hanok, Methushelah, Lemek;
\v 4 Noah, Shem, Ham, and Japheth.
\p
\v 5 The descendants of Japheth were the Cimmerians, Magog, the Medes, the Ionians, Tubal, Meshek, and Tiras.
\v 6 The descendants of the Cimmerians were Ashkenaz, Diphath, and Togarmah.
\v 7 The descendants of the Ionians were Elishah, Tartessus, Cyprus, and Rhodes.
\v 8 The descendants of Ham were Ethiopia, Egypt, Put, and Canaan.
\v 9  The descendants of Ethiopia were Seba, Havilah, Sabta, Raamah, and Sabteca. The descendants of Raamah were Sheba and Dedan.
\v 10 Ethiopia produced Nimrod, the first man on earth to be a despot.
\v 11 From Egypt sprang Lud, the Anamim, the Libyans, the Naphtuhim,
\v 12 Pathros, the Casluhim, and Crete (from which the Philistines came).
\v 13 From Canaan sprang Sidon first of all, then the Hittites,
\v 14 the Jebusites, the Amorites, the Girgashites,
\v 15 the Hivites, the Arkites, the Sinites,
\v 16 the Arvadites, the Zemarites, and the Hamathites.
\p
\v 17 The descendants of Shem were Elam, Assyria, Axpachshad, the Lydians, Aram, Uz, Hul, Gether, and Meshek.
\v 18 From Arpachshad sprang Shelah, and from Shelah Eber.
\v 19 Two sons were born to Eber, one called Peleg (Division) because the inhabitants of the earth were divided up in his day, and his brother called Joktan.
\v 20 From Joktan sprang Almodad, Sheleph, Hazarmaveth, Jerah,
\v 21 Hadoram, Uzal, Diklah,
\V 22 Ebal, Abimael, Sheba,
\v 23 Ophir, Hav­ilah, and Jobab; all these were descendants of Joktan.
\p
\v 24 Shem, Arpachshad, Shelah;
\v 25 Eber, Peleg, Reu;
\v 26 Serug, Nahor, Terah;
\v 27 Abram (that is, Abraham).
\p
\v 28 The sons of Abraham were Isaac and Ishmael,
\v 29 and these are their descendants. Ishmael's sons were Nebaioth the eldest, then Kedar, Adbeel, Mibsam,
\v 30 Mishma, Dumah, 30 Massa, Hadad, Tema,
\v 31 Jetur, Naphish, and Kedemah; these are Ishmael's sons.
\p
\v 32 Abraham's concubine Keturah bore sons, Zimran, Jokshan, Medan, Midian, Ishbak, and Shuah. Jokshan was the father of Sheba and Dedan,
\v 33 and from Midian sprang Ephah, Epher, Hanok, Abida, and El- daah; all these were descended from Keturah.
\p
\v 34 Abraham was the father of Isaac, and Isaac's sons were Esau and Israel.
\v 35 Esau's sons were Eliphaz, Reuel, Jeush, Jalam, and Korah.
\v 36 Eliphaz was the father of Teman, Omar, Zephi, Gatam, Kenaz, Timna, and Amalek;
\v 37 Reuel was the father of Nahath, Zerah, Shammah, and Mizzah.
\v 38 The sons of Seir were Lotan, Shobal, Zibeon, Anah, Dishon, Ezer, and Rishan;
\v 39 Lotan's children were Hori and Homam, Lotan's sister being Timna;
\v 40 Shobal's children were Alian, Manahath, Ebal, Shephi, and Onam; Zibeon's children were Aiah and Anah.
\v 41 Anah was the father of Dishon, and Dishon's children were Hamran, Eshban, Ithran, and Keran.
\v 42 Ezer's children were Bilhan, Zaavan, and Jaakan; Rishan’s children were Uz and Aran.
\pb
\v 43 Here are the kings who reigned in the land of Edom, before any king reigned over the Israelites. Bela the son of Beor, whose capital was Dinhabah,
\v 44 died and was succeeded by Jobab the son of Zerah, of Busaireh.
\v 45 Jobab died and was succeeded by Husham from the Temanite country.
\v 46 Husham died and was succeeded by Hadad the son of Bedad, who defeated the Midianites in the open country of Moab; the name of his capital was Avith.
\v 47 Hadad died and was succeeded by Samlah of Masrekah.
\v 48 Samlah died and was succeeded by Saul from Rahaba on the Euphrates.
\v 49 Saul died and was succeeded by Baal-hanan the son of Achbor.
\v 50 Baal-hanan died and was succeeded by Hadad; the name of his capital was Pai, and his wife was called Mehetabel, the daughter of Matred, who was the daughter of Mezahab.
\v 51 Hadad died.
\p The chieftains of Edom were the chieftain of Timna, the chieftain of Alvah, the chieftain of Jetheth,
\v 52 the chieftain of Oholibamah, the chieftain of Elath, the chieftain of Punon,
\v 53 the chieftain of Kenaz, the chieftain of Teman, the chieftain of Mibzar,
\v 54 the chieftain of Magdiel, and the chieftain of Iram; these were the chieftains of Edom.
\c 2
\p
\v 1 The sons of Israel were Reuben, Simeon, Levi, Judah, Issachar, Zebulun,
\v 2 Dan, Joseph, Benjamin, Naphtali, Gad, and Asher.
\v 3 The sons of Judah were Er, Onan, and Shelah, born to him by Bathshua the Canaanite woman. (Er, Judah's first­born, was a Wicked man before the Eternal, who cut him off.)
\v 4 His daughter-in-law Tamar also bore him Perez and Zerah; so Judah had five sons in all.
\v 5 The sons of Perez were Hezron and Hamul;
\v 6 the sons of Zerah were Zimri, Ethan, Heman, Kalkol, and Darda, five in all.
\v 7 (Karmi's son was Achar, the obstacle to Israel, who broke faith over the doomed plunder.)
\v 8 Ethan's son was Azariah.
\p
\v 9 Hezron's sons, born to him, were Jerahmeel, Ram, and Chelubai (Caleb).
\v 10 Ram was the father of Amminadab, Amminadab was the father of Nahshon the chief of the Judahites,
\v 11 Nahshon the father of Salma, Salma of Boaz,
\v 12 Boaz of Obed, and Obed of Jesse;
\v 13 Jesse was the father of Eliah, his eldest son, Abinadab his second, Shimea his third,
\v 14 Nethanel his fourth, Raddai his fifth,
\v 15 Ozem his sixth, and David his seventh,
\v 16 their sisters being Zerulah and Abigail; Zeruiah was the mother of Abishai, Joab, and Asahel, three sons;
\v 17 Abigail was the mother of Amasa, whose father was Jether the Ishmaelite.
\p
\v 18 Caleb the son of Hezron married Azubah, daughter of Jerioth, and she bore him Jesher, Shobab, and Ardon.
\v 19 When Azubah died, Caleb married Ephrath, who bore him Hur;
\v 20 Hur was the father of Uri, and Uri the father of Bezalel.
\v 21 (Later on, Hezron had intercourse with the daughter of Machir the father of Gilead, whom he married when he was sixty; she bore him Segub,
\v 22 the father of Jair, who held twenty-three towns in Gilead,
\v 23 though Havvoth-Jair and Kenath with its sixty villages were seized by Geshur and Aram. All these were descendants of Machir the father of Gilead.)
\v 24 It was after the death of Hezron that Caleb had intercourse with Ephrath. his father's
\pb wife, who bore him Ashhur the founder of Tekoa.
\v 25 Hezron's eldest son Jerahmeel was the father of Ram his eldest son, and of Bunah, Oren, and Ozem, his brothers.
\v 26 By another wife, called Atarah, Jerahmeel was the father of Onam.
\v 27 The sons of Ram, Jerahmeel's eldest son, were Maaz, Jamin, and Eker;
\v 28 the sons of Onam were Shammai and Jada. Shammai was the father of Nadab and Abishur.
\v 29 Abishur's wife was called Abihail, and she bore him Ahban and Molid;
\v 30 Nadab's sons were Seled and Appaim; Seled died childless,
\v 31 but Appaim was the father of Ishi, Ishi the father of Sheshan, and Sheslian the father of Ahlai.
\v 32 Shammai's brother Jada was the father of Jether and Jonathan; Jether died childless,
\v 33 but Jonathan was the father of Peleth and Zaza. These were the descendants of Jerahmeel.
\v 34 Sheshan had no sons only daughters; he had an Egyptian slave called Jarha,
\v 35 so to Jarha his slave Shelah gave one of his daughters in marriage. She was the mother of Attai,
\v 36 the father of Nathan, the father of Zabad,
\v 37 the father of Ephlal, the father of Obed,
\v 38 the father of Jehu, the father of Azariah,
\v 39 the father of Helez, the father of Eleasah,
\v 40 the father of Sismai, the father of Shallum,
\v 41 the father of Jekamiah, the father of Elishama.
\p
\v 42 Caleb, Jerahmeel's brother, was the father of Mareshah his eldest son, and Mareshah was the founder of Ziph and of Hebron.
\v 43 From Hebron sprang Korah, Tappuah, Rekem, and Shema;
\v 44 from Shema Raham, the founder of Jokdeam, and from Rekem Shammai,
\v 45 from Shammai Maon, and from Maon Bethzur.
\v 46 Ephah, Caleb's concubine, bore Haran, Moza, and Gazez; and Haran was the father of Gazez.
\v 47 Maakah, Caleb's concubine, bore Sheber and Tirhanah.
\v 48 The sons of his concubine Jahdai were Regem, Jotham, Geshan, Pelet, Ephah, and Shaaph;
\v 49 Shaaph was the founder of Madmannah, Sheva of Machbena and of Gibea, while Achsah was the daughter of Caleb.
\v 50 These were the descendants of Caleb.
\p
\v 51 The sons of Hur, the eldest son of Ephrathah, were Shobal the founder of Kiriath-jearim,
\v 52 Salma the founder of Betblehem, and Hareph the founder of Bethgader.
\v 53 From Shobal, the founder of Kiriath-jearim, sprang Reaiah and half of the Manahathites; from the families of Kiriath-jearim, the Ithrites, the Puthites, the Shumathites, and the Mishraites, sprang the Zorathites and the Eshtaolites.
\v 54 Salma was the founder of Bethlehem, the Netophatbites, Ataroth-beth-joab, half of the Manahathites, and the Zorites.
\v 55 The Tirathites, the Shimeathites, and the Sueathites were families of scribes who lived at Jabez; they were Kenites, descended from Hammath the founder of the Rechabites.
\c 3
\p
\v 1 Here are the sons born to o David at Hebron; the eldest & was Amnon, whose mother was Ahinoam from Jezreel, the second was Daniel, whose mother was Abigail from Karmel,
\v 2 the third was Absalom, whose mother was Maakah the daughter of Talmai king of Geshur, the fourth was Adonijah, whose mother was Haggith,
\v 3 the fifth was Shephatiah, whose mother was Abital, the sixth was Ithream, whose mother was Eglalh,
\pb
\v 4 These six were born to him at Hebron, where he reigned for seven years and six months. At Jerusalem he reigned for thirty-three years,
\v 5 and at Jerusalem there were born to him Shimea, Shobab, Nathan, and Solomon (these four being the sons of Bathshua the daughter of Ammiel),
\v 6 with Ibhar, Elishua,
\v 7 Nepheg, Japhia,
\v 8 Elishama, Baaljoda, and Eliphelet.
\v 9 All these were sons of David, in addition to the sons of his concubines; and Tamar was their sister.
\p
\v 10 Solomon was the father of Rehoboam, Rehoboam of Abijah, Abijah of Asa, Asa of Jehoshaphat, Jehoshaphat of Joram,
\v 11 Joram of Ahaziah, Ahaziah of Joash,
\v 12 Joash of Amaziah, Amaziah of Azariah, Azariah of Jotham, Jotham of Ahaz,
\v 13 Ahaz of Hezekiah, Hezekiah of Manasseh,
\v 14 Manasseh of Amon, and Amon of Josiah.
\v 15 Josiah's sons were Johanan, his eldest, Jehoiakim his second, Zedekiah his third, and Shallum his fourth.
\v 16 Jeconiah, son of Jehoiakim, was the father of Zedekiah;
\v 17 the sons of Jeconiah (who was taken prisoner) were Shealtiel,
\v 18 Malchiram, Pedaiah, Shenazzar, Jekamiah, Hoshama, and Nedabiah;
\v 19 Pedaiah's sons were Zerubbabel and Shimei; Zerubbabel was the father of Meshullam and Hananlah and their sister Shelomith,
\v 20 also of five sons, Hashubah, Ohel, Berechiah, Hasadiah, and Jushabhesed;
\v 21 Hananlah was the father of Pelatiah, Pelatlah of Jeshaiah, Jeshaiah of Rephaiah, Rephaiah of Arnan, Arnan of Obadiah, Obadiah of Shecaniah,
\v 22 and Shecaniah of six sons, Shemaiah, Hattush, Igal, Bariah, Neariah, and Shaphat;
\v 23 Neariah's three sons were Elioenai, Hizkiah, and Azrikam,
\v 24 while Elioenai had seven sons, Hodaviah, Eliashib, Pelaiah, Akkub, Johanan, Delaiah, and Anani.
\c 4
\p
\v 1 Judah's sons were Perez, Hezron, Caleb, Hur, and Shobal.
\v 2 Reaiah the son of Shobal was the father of Jahath, and Jahath was the father of Ahumai and Lahad; these were the Zorathite families.
\v 3 From Hur, the founder of Etan, sprang Jezreel, Ishma, and Idbash, also their sister Hazzelelponi,
\v 4 with Penuel the founder of Gedor and Ezer the founder of Hushah; these were descended from Hur, the eldest son of Ephrathah, the founder of Bethlehem.
\p
\v 5 Ashhur the founder of Tekoa had two wives, Helah and Naarah;
\v 6 Naarah bore him Ahuzzam, Hepher, and Temeni--Ashhurite families. These were Naarah's sons,
\v 7 while Helah's were Zereth, Zohar, Ethnan, and Koz.
\v 8 Koz was the founder of Anub, Zobebah, and the families of Aharhel the son of Harum.
\v 9 [[Jabez came to more honour than his kinsmen. His mother had called him Jabez (Hurt), crying, \qtIt hurt me to bear him.\qt*
\v 10 But Jabez appealed to the God of Israel, \qtOh that thou wouldest prosper me and enlarge my lot! Oh that thine hand might aid me! Oh that thou wouldest ward me from evil, that no hurt may befall me!\qt* And God granted him what he asked.]]
\v 11 Caleb the brother of Shuhah was the founder of Mehir, and Mehir of Eshton.
\v 12 From Eshton sprang Bethrapha, Paseah, and Tehinnah the founder of the town of Nahash. These were Rechabites.
\v 13 Kenaz was the father of Othniel and Seraiah. Othniel of Hatbath
\v 14 and
\pb Meonothai, Meonothai of Ophrah; Seraiah was the father of Joab, founder of Craftsvale (for they were craftsmen).
\p
\v 15 The sons of Caleb the son of Jephunneh were Iru, Elah, and Naam, and Elah was the father of Kenaz.
\v 16 The sons of Jehallelel were Ziph, Ziphah, Tiria, and Asarel;
\v 17-18 the sons of Ezrah were Jether, Mered, Epher, and Jalon. The children of Bithiah, daughter of the Pharaoh, who married Mered and bore children to him, were Miriam, Shammai, and Ishbah the founder of Eshtemoa, whose wife, a Jewess, bore Jered the founder of Gedor and Heber the founder of Soko and Jekuthiel the founder of Zanoah.
\v 19 [[The sons of the wife of Hodiah, the sister of Naham, were the Gar- mite founder of Keilah and the Maacathite founder of Eshtemoa.]]
\v 20 [[The sons of Shimon were Amnon, Rinnah, Benhanan, and Tilon.]] [[Zoheth was the son of Ishi, and . . . the son of Zoheth.]]
\p
\v 21 The sons of Shelah, Judah's son, were Er the founder of Lecah, Laadah the founder of Mareshah, and families of linen-workers at Beth-ashbea,
\v 22 Jokim, men of Kozeba, Joash, and Saraph who ruled in Moab and then retired to Bethlehem. This from an ancient archive.
\v 23 (These were the potters and inhabitants of Netaim and Gederah; they resided there in the service of the king.)
\p
\v 24 The sons of Simeon were Nemuel, Jamin, Jarib, Zerah, and Shaul
\v 25 the father of Sliallum, whose son was Mibsam the father of Mishma;
\v 26 Mishma's son was Hammuel, the father of Zakkur, whose son was Shimei.
\v 27 Shimei had sixteen sons and six daughters, but his brothers had not many children, nor did all their family multiply like the Judahites.
\v 28 They lived at Beersheba, Moladah, Hazarshual,
\v 29 Billiah, Ezem, Tolad,
\v 30 Bethuel, Hormah, Ziklag,
\v 31 Beth-markaboth, Hazarsusim, Beth-biri, and Shaaraim (which remained their towns till the reign of David),
\v 32 along with their respective villages; also, at Ether, Ainrimmon, Token, and Ashan, these four towns along
\v 33 with all their villages as far as Baal. These were their settlements, and they kept a genealogical record.
\p
\v 34 Meshhobab, Jamlech, Joshah 34 the son of Amazlah,
\v 35 Joel, Jehu the son of Joshibiah (whose father was Seraiah the son of Asiel),
\v 36 Elioenai, Jaakobah, Jeshohaiah, Asaiah, Adiel, Jesimiel, Benaiah,
\v 37 and Ziza (whose father was Shiphi the son of Allon, the son of Jedaiah, the son of Shimri, the son of Shemaiah);
\v 38 these men here mentioned were chieftains, and their families prospered mightily.
\v 39 They went in search of pasture for their flocks to the entrance of Gerar, to the eastern side of the valley,
\v 40 where they found rich, excellent pasture, and a broad, quiet, peaceable countryside. (The inhabitants used to belong to the Hamites.)
\v 41 So during the reign of Hezekiah king of Judah the folk here mentioned went and destroyed the tents of the inhabitants, exterminating the Meunim who were to be found there, and taking their place, since there was pasture for their flocks there.
\v 42 Five hundred of these Simeonites also attacked mount Seir, led by Pelatiah, Neariah, Rephaiah, and Uzziel, the sons of Ishi;
\v 43 they defeated the
\pb surviving Amalekites who had escaped, and to this day they live there.
\c 5
\p
\v 1 Now for the sons of Reuben the eldest son of Israel. (He was the eldest, but, as he polluted his father's marriage-bed, his birthright was assigned to the sons of Joseph, Israel's son; although Joseph is not entered in the genealogy according to the birthright. The birthright did belong to Joseph,
\v 2 but Judah was more powerful than his brothers, and from him came the leadership.)
\v 3 The sons of Reuben, Israel's eldest son, were Hanok, Pallu, Hezron, and Karmi.
\v 4 The sons of Joel were Shemaiah, Gog, Shimri,
\v 5 Micah, Reaiah, Baal,
\v 6 and Beerah, whom the Assyrian king Tilgath-pilneser carried off into exile--Beerah was a Reubenite chieftain,
\v 7 and his kinsmen, reckoned by families in the genealogical records, were Jeiel the chief, then Zechariah,
\v 8 and Bela the son of Azaz, the son of Shema, the son of Joel, whose settlements at Aroer reached the length of Nebo and Baalmeon,
\v 9 and stretched eastward as far as the opening of the desert ending at the river Euphrates--so numerous were their cattle in Gilead.
\v 10 (During the reign of Saul the Reubenites attacked the Hagrites and cut them to pieces, occupying all their territory east of Gilead.)
\p
\v 11 Opposite them lived the sons of Gad, occupying the land of Bashan as far as Salecah.
\v 12 Joel the chief, Shapham, Janai, and Shaphat in Bashan,
\v 13 with their seven fellow-clansmen Michael, Meshullam, Sheba, Jorai, Jakan, Zia, and Eber,
\v 14 were sons of Abihail (the son of Huri, the son of Jaroah, the son of Gilead, the son of Michael, the son of Jehishai, the son of Jahdo, the son of Buz . . .
\v 15 Ahi, the son of Abdiel), all chiefs in their clan;
\v 16 they lived in Gilead, in Bashan, in the townships, and in all the pasture lands of Sirion to their fullest extent.
\v 17 These Gadites were all enrolled in the genealogical registers during the reign of Jotham king of Judah and during the reign of Jeroboam king of Israel.
\p
\v 18 The Reubenites, the Gadites, and the half-clan of Manasseh, brave fighters, able to carry shield and sword, good archers, and skilled warriors, amounted to forty-four thousand seven hundred and sixty men, fit for active service.
\v 19 They attacked the Hagrites, and also Jetur, Naphish, and Nodab.
\v 20 God helped them and put the Hagrites and all their allies into their power; for they cried to God as they fought, and he answered them because they relied on him.
\v 21 They carried off the enemy's cattle, fifty thousand camels, two hundred and fifty thousand sheep, two thousand asses, and also a hundred thousand prisoners.
\v 22 Many of the enemy were also slain, for the war was with God's sanction. Down to the exile, they lived in the dispossessed territory.
\p
\v 23 The members of the half-clan of Manasseh who lived in the country swarmed from Bashan to Baal-hermon and Senir or mount Hermon.
\v 24 Their chiefs were Epher, Ishi, Eliel, Azriel, Jeremiah, Hodaviah, and Jahdiel, great fighters, famous men, and chiefs of the clan.
\v 25 But they broke faith with the God of their fathers and went faithlessly after the gods of the naives whom God had destroyed
\pb before them.
\v 26 So the God of Israel roused up Pulu the king of Assyria and Tilgath-pilneser the king of Assyria, who carried them into exile, the Reubenites and the Gadites and the half­clan of Manasseh, taking them to Halah, Habor, Hara, and the river of Gozan, where they are to this day.
\c 6
\p
\v 1 The sons of Levi were Gershon, Kohath, and Merari.
\v 2 The sons of Kohath were Amram, Izhar, Hebron, and Uzziel;
\v 3 Amram's children were Aaron, Moses, and Miriam; and Aaron's sons were Nadab, Abihu, Eleazar, and Ithamar.
\v 4 Eleazar was the father of Phinehas,
\v 5 Phinehas of Abishua, Abishua of Bukki, Bukki of Uzzi,
\v 6 Uzzi of Zerahiah, Zerahiah of Meraioth,
\v 7 Meraioth of Amariah, Amariah of Ahitub,
\v 8 Ahitub of Zadok, Zadok of Ahimaaz,
\v 9 Ahimaaz of Azariah, Azariah of Johanan,
\v 10 Johanan of Azariah (it was he who officiated as priest in Solomon's temple at Jerusalem),
\pb
\v 11 Azariah of Amariah, Amariah of Ahitub,
\v 12 Ahitub of Zadok, Zadok of Shallum,
\v 13 Shallum of Hilkiah, Hilkiah of Azariah,
\v 14 Azariah of Seraiah, and Seraiah of Jehozadak;
\v 15 Jehozadak went into exile when the Eternal made Nebuchadnezzar carry off the men of Judah and Jerusalem.
\p
\v 16 The sons of Levi were Gershom, Kohath, and Merari.
\v 17 Libni and Shimei, these are the names of Gershom's sons;
\v 18 Kohath's sons were Amram, Izhar, Hebron, and Uzziel;
\v 19 Merari's sons were Mahli and Mushi. Such were the families of the Levites, one by one.
\v 20 From Gershom sprang Libni, from Libni Jahath, from Jahath Zimmah,
\v 21 from Zimmah Joah, from Joah lddo, from Iddo Zerah, and from Zerah Jeatherai.
\p
\v 22 The line of descent from Kohath was Amminadab, Korah, Assir,
\v 23 Elkanah, Ebiasaph, Assir,
\v 24 Tahath, Uriel, Uzziah, and Shaul.
\v 25 The line of descent from Elkanah was Amasai, Ahimoth,
\v 26 Elkanah, Zophai, Nahath,
\v 27 Eliab, Jeroham, Elkanah,
\v 28 and Samuel. Samuel's sons were Joel his eldest and Abiah his second.
\v 29 The line of descent from Merari was Mahli, Libni, Shimei, Uzzah,
\v 30 Shimea, Haggiah, and Asaiah.
\p
\v 31 Here are the men whom David put in charge of the service of song in the temple of the Eternal, after the ark was settled there;
\v 32 they carried on the service of song at the Trysting tent, till Solomon had built the temple of the Eternal at Jerusalem, fulfilling their office in due order.
\v 33 Those in office and their descendants were as follows: to the Kohathites belonged Heman the singer (the son of Joel, the son of Samuel,
\v 34 the son of Elkanah, the son of Jeroham, the son of Eliel, the son of Toah,
\v 35 the son of Zuph, 35 the son of Elkanah, the son of Mahath, the son of Amasai,
\v 36 the son of Elkanah, the son of Joel, the son of Azariah, the son of Zephaniah,
\v 37 the son of Tahath, the son of Assir, the son of Ebiasaph, the son of Korah,
\v 38 the son of Izhar, the son of Kohath, the son of Levi, the son of Israel);
\v 39 his brother Asaph, who stood at his right hand, was Asaph the son of Bereehiah, the son of Shimea,
\v 40 the son of Michael, the son of Baaseiah, the son of Malchijah,
\v 41 the son of Ethni, the son of Zerah, the son of Adaiah,
\v 42 the son of Ethan, the
\pb son of Zimmah, the son of Shimei,
\v 43 the son of Jahath, the son of Gershom, the son of Levi.
\v 44 At their left hand stood their brothers, the sons of Merari, represented by Ethan the son of Kishi, the son of Abdi, the son of Malluch,
\v 45 the son of Hashabiah, the son of Amazlah, the son of Hilkiah,
\v 46 the son of Amzi, the son of Bani, the son of Shemer,
\v 47 the son of Mahli, the son of Mushi, the son of Merari, the son of Levi.
\v 48 (Their fellow-Levites were put in charge of all the duties of the tent of God's house.
\v 49 But Aaron and his sons officiated at the altar of burnt-offering and at the altar of incense, doing all that was required in the most sacred place, and making expiation for Israel, in keeping with all the orders issued by Moses the servant of God.)
\v 50 The line of Aaron's descendants was Eleazar, Phinehas, Abishua,
\v 51 Bukki, Uzzi, Zerahiah,
\v 52 Meraioth, Amariah, Ahitub,
\v 53 Zadok, and Ahimaaz.
\p
\v 54 The following are their residences, as they were settled within the boundaries of the land. To the descendants of Aaron who belonged to the Kohathite family--for theirs was the first lot--
\v 55 were assigned Hebron and its open lands in Judah,
\v 56 though the fields and villages belonging to the town were assigned to Caleb the son of Jephunneh.
\v 57 To the descendants of Aaron were assigned Hebron, the town of refuge, Libnah with its open lands, Jattir, Eshtemoa with its open lands,
\v 58 Hilen with its open lands, Debir with its open lands,
\v 59 Ashan with its open lands, and Beth-shemesh with its open lands,
\v 60 besides (from the clan of Benjamin) Geba with its open lands, Allemeth with its open lands, and Anathoth with its open lands. Thirteen towns in all they had, among their fam­ilies.
\p
\v 61 The rest of the Kohathites had ten towns allotted to them from the families of the clans of Ephraim and of Dan and the half-clan of Manasseh.
\v 62 The Gershomites were allotted thirteen towns for their families, from the clans of Issachar, Asher, Naphtali, and Manasseh in Bashan.
\v 63 The Merarites were allotted twelve towns for their families, from the clans of Reuben, Gad, and Zebulun.
\v 64 The Israelites allotted the Levites these towns along with their open lands.
\v 65 (They assigned the towns now to be mentioned, from the clans of Judah, Simeon, and Benjamin.)
\v 66 Some of the Kohathite families had towns allotted to them from the clan of Ephraim;
\v 67 they were assigned the town of refuge Shechem in the highlands of Ephraim with its open lands, Gezer with its open lands,
\v 68 Jokmeam with its open lands, Beth-horon with its open lands,
\v 69 Aijalon with its open lands, Gathrimmon with its open lands, and--
\v 70 from the half-clan of Manasseh--Aner with its open lands, and Bileam with its open lands, for the rest of the Ko­hathite families.
\v 71 The Gershomites were assigned, from the family of the half-clan of Manasseh, Golan in Bashan with its open lands, Ashtaroth with its open lands,
\v 72 and--from the clan of Issachar--Kedesh with its open lands, Daberath with its open lands,
\v 73 Ramoth with its open lands, Anem with its open lands, besides--
\v 74 from the clan of Asher--Mashal with its open lands, Abdon with its
\pb open lands,
\v 75 Hukok with its open lands, Rehob with its open lands,
\v 76 and--from the clan of Naphtali--Kedesh in Galilee with its open lands, Hammon with its open lands, and Kiriathaim with its open lands.
\v 77 To the rest of the Levites, the Merarites, were assigned, from the clan of Zebulun, Rimmono with its open lands, Tabor with its open lands,
\v 78 and, across the Jordan at Jericho, east of the Jordan, from the clan of Reuben, Bezer in the desert with its open lands, Jahzah with its open lands,
\v 79 Kedemoth with its open lands, and Mephaath with its open lands,
\v 80 besides--from the clan of Gad--Ramoth in Gilead with its open lands, Mahanaim with its open lands,
\v 81 Heshbon with its open lands, and Jazer with its open lands.
\c 7
\v 1 The sons of Issachar were four, Tola, Puah, Jashub, and Shimron.
\v 2 Tola's sons were Uzzi, Rephaiah, Jeriel, Jahmai, Jibsam, and Samuel, chiefs of their families, mighty warriors in their generation, their families in the reign of David amounting to twenty-two thousand six hundred men.
\v 3 Uzzi's son, Izrahiah, was the father of Michael, Obadiah, Joel, and Isshiah, all five men being chiefs;
\v 4 along with them, duly entered in the family genealogies, were armed forces numbering thirty-six thousand men; for they had many wives and sons.
\v 5 The total reckoning of the families of Issachar, by their genealogical records, was eighty-seven thousand brave warriors.
\p
\v 6 The sons of Benjamin were three, Bela, Becher, and Jediael.
\v 7 Bela's sons were five, Ezbon, Uzzi, Uzziel. Jerimoth. and Iri, mighty warriors, chiefs of their families, which in the genealogies were reckoned as twenty-two thousand and thirty-four men.
\v 8 The sons of Becher were Zemirah, Joash, Eliezer, Elioenai, Omri, Jeremoth, Abijah, Anathoth, and Alemeth--all sons of Becher;
\v 9 they were reckoned in the genealogies as mighty warriors, chiefs of their families, which numbered twenty thousand two hundred men.
\v 10 Jediael's son was Bilhan, the father of Jeush, Benjamin, Ebub, Kenaanah, Zethan, Tarshish, and Ahishahar;
\v 11 all these were descendants of Jediael, mighty warriors as chiefs of their families, which amounted to seventeen thousand two hundred men, fit for active service.
\v 12 (Also Shuppim and Huppim, sons of Ir, with Hushim the son of Aher.)
\p
\v 13 The sons of Naphtali were Jahziel, Guni, Jezer, and Shal- lum; their mother was Bilhah.
\p
\v 14 The children of Manasseh, borne to him by an Aramite concubine, were Machir the father of Gilead
\v 15 (who married a wife called Maakah), his sister named Hammoleketh, and his brother Zelophehad; Zelophehad had daughters.
\v 16 Maakah the wife of Gilead bore a son, whom she called Peresh; the name of his brother was Sheresh, and his sons were Ulam and Rekem;
\v 17 Ulam was the father of Bedan. These were the descendants of Gilead son of Machir, son of Manasseh.
\v 18 His sister Hammoleketh was the mother of Ishhod, Abiezer, and Mahlah.
\v 19 Shemida's sons were Ahian, Shechem, Likhi, and Aniam.
\p
\v 20 The line of Ephraim was Shuthelah, Tahath, Eleadah . . .
\v 21 Ezer and Elead, whom the natives of Gath killed because they
\pb had come down to raid their cattle.
\v 22 Ephraim their father mourned many a day for them, and his brothers came to comfort him.
\v 23 Then he went in to his wife, who conceived and bore a son; Ephraim called him Beriah (On-evil), because his family had fallen on evil days.
\v 24 His daughter was Sheerah, who built both upper and lower Beth-horon, and Uzzen-sheerah.
\v 25 Rephah and Resheph were his sons, Resheph the father of Telah, the father of Tahan,
\v 26 the father of Ladan, the father of Ammihud, the father of Elishama,
\v 27 the father of Nun, the father of Joshua.
\v 28 Their possessions and settlements were Bethel with its townships, East Naaran, West Gezer with its townships, Shechem with its townships, and on to Azzah and its townships; also,
\v 29 along the frontier of Manasseh, Beth-shean with its townships, Taanak with its townships, Megiddo with its townships, and Dor with its townships. There dwelt the descendants of Joseph the son of Israel.
\p
\v 30 The sons of Asher were Imnah, Ishvah, Ishvi, Beraiah, and their sister Serah;
\v 31 Beraiah was the father of Heber and Malchiel, Malchiel the father of Birzaith;
\v 32 Heber was the father of Japhlet, Shemer, Hotham, and Shua their sister;
\v 33 Japhlet's sons were Pasaeh, Bimhal, and Ashvath. These were Japhlet's sons;
\v 34 the sons of his brother Shemer were Rogah, Jehubbah, and Aram,
\v 35 and the sons of his brother Hotham were Zophah, Imna, Shelesh, and Amal.
\v 36 Zophah was the father of Suah, Harnepher, Shual, Beri, Imrah,
\v 37 Bezer, Hod, Shamma, Shilshah, Jithran, and Beera;
\v 38 and Jithran's sons were Jephunneh, Pispah, and Ara.
\v 39 [[Ulla's sons were Ara, Hanniel, and Rizia.]]
\v 40 All these were Asherite chiefs, picked soldiers of prowess, paramount chieftains. Their forces, reckoned in the genealogies, for active service, were twenty-six thousand men.
\c 8
\p
\v 1 Benjamin's sons were Bela, his eldest, Ashbel the second, Aharah the third,
\v 2 Nohah the fourth, and Rapha the fifth.
\v 3-5 Bela became the father of Addar, Gera (father of Ehud), Abishua, Naaman, Ahoah, Shephuphan, and Huram.
\v 6-8 The sons of Ehud, heads of families in Geba, were Iglaam and Alemeth; Iglaam became the father of Uzza and Ashishahar, and in the open country of Moab he became the father of Mesha their sister and Hushim (who married Baara).
\v 9 Ashishahar became the father of Jobab, Zibia, Mesha, Malkam,
\v 10 Jeuz, Shachia, and Mirma; these were his sons, chiefs of their families.
\v 11 Hushim became the father of Abitub, Elpaal
\v 12 (he built Ono, Lud, and their townships),
\v 13 Beriah, and Shema (both of whom, as family chiefs of the natives of Aijalon, routed the men of Gath),
\v 14 with their brothers Shashak and Jeremoth.
\v 15 Beriah's sons were Zebadiah, Arad, Eder,
\v 16 Michael, Ishpah, and Joha;
\v 17 Elpaal's sons were Zebadiah, Meshullam, Hizki, Heber,
\v 18 Ishmerai, Izliah, and Jobab;
\v 19 Shema's sons were Jakim, Zichri, Zabdi,
\v 20 Elienai, Zillethai, Eliel,
\v 21 Adaiah, Beraiah, and Shimrath.
\v 22 Shashak's sons were Ishpan, Eber, Eliel,
\v 23 Abdon, Zichri, Hanan,
\v 24 Hananiah, Elam, Anthothijah,
\v 25 Iphdeiah, and Penuel.
\v 26 Jeremoth's sons were Shamsherai, Shehariah, Athaliah,
\pb
\v 27 Jaareshiah, Elijah, and Zichri.
\p
\v 28 These were family chiefs, by their genealogies, leading men, who lived at Jerusalem.
\p
\v 29 At Gibeon lived the founder of Gibeon, Jeuel, whose wife was called Maakah;
\v 30 his eldest son was Abdon, then Zur, Kish, Baal, Ner, Nadab,
\v 31 Gedor, Ahio, Zecher,
\v 32 and Mikloth (the father of Shimeam). They also lived at Jerusalem, opposite their fellow-clansmen.
\v 33 Ner was the father of Abner, Kish of Saul, Saul of Jonathan, Malchishua, Abinadab, and Eshbaal;
\v 34 Jonathan's son was Merib-baal, the father of Micah,
\v 35 and Micah's sons were Pithon, Melek, Tarea, and Ahaz.
\v 36 Ahaz was the father of Jehoaddah, whose sons were Alemeth, Azmaveth, and Zimri, Zimri the father of Moza,
\v 37 whose son was Binea, the father of Raphah, whose son was Eleasah, the father of Azel;
\v 38 Azel had six sons, called Azrikam, Bokru, Ishmael, Sheariah, Obadiah, and Hanan. All these were Azel's sons;
\v 39 his brother Eshek was the father of three, Ulam, Jeush, and Eliphelet.
\v 40 Ulam's sons were mighty warriors, archers; they had many sons and grandsons, a hundred and fifty of them. All these belonged to the Benjamites.
\c 9
\p
\v 1 All Israel was registered in genealogies; the records lie in the Book of the Kings of Israel. Owing to their transgressions, the Jews were carried off into exile at Babylon.
\p
\v 2 The first to re-inhabit their settlements and towns were the laity of Israel, the priests, the Levites, and the temple-attendants,
\v 3 though some Judahites, Benjamites, Ephraimites, and Manassites also resided at Jerusalem,
\v 4 namely, Uthai the son of Ammihud (the son of Omri, the son of Imri, the son of Bani), belonging to the sons of Pharez the son of Judah,
\v 5 Asaiah the oldest member of the Shilonites, with his sons,
\v 6 Jeuel and his fellow-Zerahites, numbering six hundred and ninety,
\v 7-9 and nine hundred and fifty-six registered Benjamites, including Sallu the son of Meshullam (the son of Judah the son of Hasenuah), Ibneiah the son of Jeroham, Elah the son of Uzzi (the son of Michri), and Meshullam the son of Shephatiah (the son of Reuel, the son of Ibnijah); all these men were chiefs of their respective families.
\v 10 The priests were Jedaiah, Jehoiarib, Jachin,
\v 11 and Azariah the son of Hilkiah, the son of Meshullam, the son of Zadok, the son of Meraioth, the son of Ahitub, the chief authority in the house of God,
\v 12 with Adaiah the son of Jeroham, the son of Pashhur, the son of Malchijah, and Maasai the son of Adiel, the son of Jahzerah, the son of Meshullam, the son of Meshillemith, the son of Immer,
\v 13 besides their fellows, family chiefs, one thousand seven hundred and sixty most efficient men for the duties of service in the house of God.
\v 14 The Levites were Shemaiah son of Hasshub, the son of Azrikam, the son of Hashabiah, a Merarite,
\v 15 with Bakbakkar, Heresh, Galal, and Mattaniah son of Mica, the son of Zichri, the son of Asaph,
\v 16 also Obadiah son of Shemaiah, the son of Galal, the son of Jeduthun, and Berechiah the son of Asa, the son of Elkanah, who resided in the villages of the Netophathites.
\v 17 The warders were Shallum, Akkub, Talmon, Ahiman, and their kinsmen; Shallum was
\pb their head,
\v 18 stationed till now at the king's gate on the east. These were the warders of the sacred camp of the Levites.
\v 19 Shallum son of Kore, the son of Ebiasaph, the son of Korah, with his fellow-Korahites of that family, were in charge of the service as keepers of the sacred thresholds, as their fathers had been keepers of the entrance in the sacred camp of the Eternal,
\v 20 when Phinehas the son of Eleazar ruled them (may the Eternal be with him!);
\v 21 Zechariah the son of Meshelemiah kept the door of the Trysting tent.
\v 22 All these, selected as warders at the entry, numbered two hundred and twelve. They were reckoned by their genealogies within their villages, appointed to their responsible duties by David and Samuel the seer;
\v 23 they and their sons had charge of the gates of the house of the Eternal (the Tent-house) as guards,
\v 24 acting as warders on the east, the west, the north, and the south sides of it.
\v 25 Their fellows in the villages had to come in periodically, every seven days, to join them,
\v 26 since four head warders, who were Levites, were constantly on duty, in charge of the chambers and the treasuries of the house of God,
\v 27 lodging in the vicinity of the house of God, as they bore the duty of watching it and were responsible for opening it every morning.
\v 28 Some of them had charge of the utensils of the service, which had to be counted when they were brought in and taken out.
\v 29 Others looked after the furniture and all the sacred utensils, as well as the flour, the wine, the oil, the incense, and the spices.
\v 30 Others, belonging to the priests, prepared the spices and cooked them.
\v 31 Mattithiah, a Levite, the eldest son of Shallum the Korahite, was responsible for the pastry of flat cakes,
\v 32 and some of the other Kohathites looked after the bread of the Presence, preparing it every sabbath.
\p
\v 33 [[These were the singers, family chiefs of the Levites, who lived in the temple-chambers, exempt from all other service, since they were on duty day and night.]]
\v 34 [[These were family chiefs of the Levites, reckoned by their genealogies, leading men, who lived at Jerusalem.]]
\p
\v 35 [[At Gibeon lived the founder of Gibeon, Jeiel, whose wife was called Maakah;
\v 36 his eldest son was Abdon, then Zur, Kish, Baal, Ner, Nadab,
\v 37 Gedor, Ahio, Zechariah, and Mikloth
\v 38 (the father of Shimeam). They also lived at Jerusalem, opposite their fellow-clansmen.
\v 39 Ner was the father of Kish, Kish of Saul, Saul of Jonathan, Malchishua, Abinadab, and Eshbaal;
\v 40 Jonathan's son was Merib-baal, the father of Micah,
\v 41 and Micah's sons were Pithon, Melek, and Tahrea.
\v 42 Ahaz was the father of Jarah, Jarah of Alemeth, Azmaveth, and Zimri, Zimri the father of Moza,
\v 43 whose son was Binea, the father of Rephaiah, the father of Eleasah, whose son was Azel;
\v 44 Azel had six sons, called Azrikam, Bokru, Ishmael, Sheariah, Obadiah, and Hanan; these were Azel's sons.]]
\c 10
\p
\v 1 When the Philistines "I A made their attack on Is- -*-U rael, the men of Israel fled from the Philistines and dropped slain upon mount Gilboa. The 2 Philistines overtook Saul and his sons; they slew Jonathan, Abina­dab, and Malchishua, Saul’s
\v 2 sons. Saul himself was hard pressed in the fight, the archers got at him, and he was wounded
\v 3 by the archers. Then Saul said to his armour-bearer, “Draw your sword and run me through, lest these uncircum­cised creatures come and make a fool of me.” But his armour-bearer would not; he was terrified. So Saul took his
\v 4 own sword and fell on it. And when his armour-bearer saw that Saul was dead, he also fell
\v 5 on his sword and died. Thus Saul died, and his three sons; his whole household died to-
\v 6 gether. (When all the men of Israel in the valley saw the flight and saw that Saul and his sons were dead, they abandoned their towns and took to flight; the Philistines then came and
\v 7 occupied them.) Next day, when the Philistines went to strip the slain, they found Saul and his sons lying dead on mount Gil-
\v 8 boa. They stripped him, cut his head off, took his armour, and sent messengers all round the Philistine country to carry the good news to their idols and
\v 9 people; his armour they placed in the temple of their gods, his head they nailed up in the tem-
\v 10 ple of Dagon. But when all the men of Jabesh-gilead heard what the Philistines had done to Saul,
\v 11 all the braves set out and re­moved the body of Saul and the bodies of his sons to Jabesh, burying their bones under the oak at Jabesh, and fasting for seven days.
\v 12 Thus died Saul, for his faith­lessness to the Eternal, because he had not kept the word of the Eternal, and also because he
\v 13 had consulted a medium, re­sorting to a medium and not to the Eternal; for this did the
Eternal kill him, turning the kingdom over to David the son of Jesse.
Then all Israel gathered -| "| round David at Hebron, As­saying, “Here we are, your own bone and flesh! In bygone days, 2 even when Saul was our king, it was you who led Israel out and in; the Eternal your God said to you, ‘You shall shepherd my people Israel, you shall be prince over my people Israel!’ ” So all 3 the sheikhs of Israel came to the king at Hebron. David made a compact with them at Hebron, in presence of the Eternal, and they anointed David king over Israel, as the Eternal had or­dered by Samuel. Then David 4 and all Israel went to Jerusalem (that is, Jebus), where the Jebu- 5 sites, natives of the country, told David, “You will never get in here.” But David did cap­ture the stronghold of Sion (which is David’s burg). David 6 proclaimed, “Whoever is the first to rout the Jebusites shall be commander-in-chief.” Joab the son of Zerulah was the first to attack them, and he was made commander. David took 7 up his residence in the strong­hold (hence it was called “Da­vid’s burg”), and built a wall 8 round about the town, from the Millo rampart onwards, while Joab repaired the rest of the town. David became greater 9 and greater, for the Lord of hosts was on his side.
These are the leading knights 10 of David, who were his power­ful supporters in the kingdom, uniting with all Israel to make him king, in terms of the Eter­nal’s instructions for Israel. This is the number of David’s 11 knights. There was Ishbaal,
the son of a Hachmonite, chief of the Trio, who once wielded his spear against three hundred men, whom he slew all at one
\v 12 	time. Next him came Eleazar the son of Dodo, the Ahohite,
\v 13 	one of the Trio of knights; he was with David at Pasdammim, in a field full of barley, where the Philistines had collected; the people had run away from the
\v 14 	Philistines, but he held his ground in the field, kept the place, and slew the Philistines; the Eternal saved them by a
\v 15 	great victory. Such were ex­ploits of the Trio of knights.
\v 16 	Abishai, the brother of Joab, was at the head of the Thirty, for he once wielded his spear against three hundred men whom he slew, and won a name
\v 17 	like that of the Trio. He was the most distinguished of the Thirty and became their cap­tain, but he was not promoted
\v 18 	to a place in the Trio. Then there was Benaiah, the son of Jehoiada, from Kabzeel, a brave fighter, a man of doughty deeds; he killed two lion-cubs in their lair, after he had gone down and killed the lion inside a pit
\v 19 	upon a snowy day. He also killed an Egyptian, a very tall man, seven and a half feet high, who carried a spear the size of a weaver’s beam; Benaiah attacked him with a club, wrenched the spear from the Egyptian’s hand, and killed him
\v 20 	with his own spear. Such were the exploits of Benaiah, the son of Jehoiada; he won a name like
\v 23 	that of the Trio of knights, and was indeed renowned among the Thirty, but he was not pro­moted to the Trio. David put him at the head of his body­guard.
\v 12 	Three of the Thirty once made
their way down to the crag, to join David at the stronghold of Adullam. The Philistine force was camping in the valley of Rephaim; David was inside the 16 stronghold, and there was a Philistine garrison at Bethle­hem. David said longingly, “Oh if someone would only 17 give me a drink of water from the well at Bethlehem, the well beside the gate!” So the three 18 broke through the Philistine lines, drew some water from the well at Bethlehem, the well be­side the gate, and brought it to David. But he would not drink it; he poured it out for the Eternal, crying, “My God for- 19 bid that I should do it! Am I to drink the blood of these men who went at the risk of their lives? For they have brought this water at the risk of their fives.” So he would not drink it.
Now for the heroes of the 26 army: Asahel the brother of Joab, Elhanan the son of Dodo (from Bethlehem), Shammoth 27 from Harod, Helez the Pelonite,
Ira the son of Ikkesh (from 28 Tekoah), Abiezer from Ana- thoth, Sibbechai the Hushath- 29 ite, Ilai the Ahohite, Maharai 30 the Netophathite, Heled the son of Baanah the Netophathite, Ithai the son of Ribai from 31 Gibeah (belonging to Benja­min), Benaiah the Pirathonite, Hiddai from the wadies of Ga- 32 ash, Abiel the Arbathite, Az- 33 maveth from Bahurim, Efiahba from Shaalbon, the sons of Ha- 34 shem from Gizon, Jonathan the son of Shage the Hararite, Ahiam the son of Sakar the 35 Hararite, Eliphal the son of Ur, Hepher from Mecherath, Eliam 36 the son of Ahithophel the Gilo- nite, Hezro from Karmel, Naarai 37 the son of Ezbai, Joel the 38
brother of Nathan, Mibhar the son of Hagri, Zelek the Am-
\v 2 	monite, Naharai the Beerothite, armour-bearer to Joab the son
\v 3 	of ZeruTah, Ira the Ithrite, Gareb the Ithrite, Uriah the
\v 4 	Hittite, Zabad the son of Ahlai,
\v 5 	Adina the son of Shiza the Reu- benite, Captain of a Reubenite
\v 6 	company of thirty, Hanan the
\v 7 	son of Maakah, Josaphat the Mithnite, Uzzia from Ashtaroth, Shama and Jehiel (their father
\v 8 	was Hotham of Aroer), Jediael the son of Shimri, and his
\v 9 	brother Joha (from Tizi), Eliel the Mahavite, Jeribai and Joshaviah (sons of Elnaam), Ith-
\v 10 	mah the Moabite, Ehel, Obed, and Jaasiel from Zobah.
Here are the men who joined David at Ziklag, when, owing to Saul the son of Kish, he had no freedom of movement; they were among the strong men who helped him
\v 2 	in the fray, they plied the bow, they could sling stones and shoot arrows with their right hand or their left, and they belonged to Saul’s own
\v 3 	clan of Benjamin. First came Ahiezer, then Joash son of Shemaiah from Gibeah, Jeziel and Pelet (sons of Azmaveth), Berachah, Jehu from Anathoth,
\v 4 	Ishmaiah the Gibeonite (a mighty member of the Thirty, whom he commanded), Jere­miah, Jahaziel, Johanan, Joza-
\v 5 	bad from Gedor, Eluzai, Jeri- moth, Bealiah, Shemariah, and Shephatiah the Haruphite, with
\v 6 	Elkanah, Isshiah, Azarel, Joe- zer, and Jashoboam, who were
\v 7 	Korahites, Joelah and Zebadiah, the sons of Jeroham from Gedor.
\v 8 	At the stronghold in the des­ert David was also joined by a nuniber of Gadite warriors of prowess, soldiers trained for war,
who could manage shield and spear, fierce-looking as lions and nimble as roes on the hill; there 9 were Ezer, at their head, Oba- diah the second, Eliab the third, Mishmannah the fourth, Jere- 10 miah the fifth, Attai the sixth, 11 Eliel the seventh, Johanan the 12 eighth, Elzabad the ninth, Jeremiah the tenth, and Mach- 13 bannai the eleventh. These were 14 the Gadite captains, the weakest a match for any hundred men, the strongest a match for a thousand. It was these men who 15 in the first month of the year forded the Jordan when it had overflowed all its banks, and routed the folk of the valleys east and west.
Some also came from Benja- 16 min and Judah to join David at the stronghold; David went out 17 to meet them, and told them, “If you come to me in peace to help me, then I am ready to join you; but if yOu come to betray me to my foes, though I have done no wrong, then may the God of our fathers take note of it and punish it!” Amasa, who 18 was commander-in-chief, was in­spired to reply,
We are your men, David, on your side, O son of Jesse! Peace, peace to you, and to your helpers peace— for your God helps you!
Then David admitted them and made them captains of his band.
Some also deserted to David 19 from Manasseh; it was when he accompanied the Philistines to fight against Saul, but gave them no help, as the Philistine authorities after deliberating on the matter sent him away, be­lieving that he would desert to Saul and cost them their lives. David then returned to Ziklag, 20 where some Manassite com­manders deserted to him, Ad-
nah, Jozabad, Jediael, Michael, Jozabad, Elibu, and Zillethai;
\v 21 	they helped David against the raiders, lor they were all war­riors of prowess and took com-
\v 22 	mand of his host—a host that grew daily by its recruits, till it became a large host, a very host of God.
\v 23 	Here are the numbers of the armed divisions that joined Da­vid at Hebron, to turn the king­dom of Saul over to him, as the
\v 24 	Eternal had declared. The Ju- dahite warriors* armed with shields and spears, were six
\v 25 	thousand eight hundred; there were seven thousand one hun­dred Simeonites, warriors of
\v 26 	prowess, four thousand six hun-
\v 27 	dred Levites, and three thou­sand seven hundred Aaronites,
\v 28 	led by Jehoiada, along with Zadok a young warrior of prow­ess, who had twenty-two cap­tains of his father’s family.
\v 29 	There were three thousand from Benjamin, Saul’s own clan, for till now the larger number of them had kept loyal to the house
\v 30 	of Saul. There were twenty thousand eight hundred warriors of prowess from Ephraim, fa­mous fighters in their families,
\v 31 	and eighteen thousand (whose names were kept) from the half­clan of Manasseh, who came to
\v 32 	make David king. There were two hundred leaders from Issa- char, men who knew the needs of the time and what exactly Israel ought to do; they had all their clansmen at their com-
\v 33 	mand. There were fifty thou­sand men from Zebulun, fit for active service, taking the field with every weapon of war, a large company with a single
